00:42:02.590 --> 00:42:05.820
and I am, to the extent
that I am at Harvard,

00:42:05.820 --> 00:42:07.680
in environments
where you see a lot

00:42:07.680 --> 00:42:14.130
of the success of the last 20,
30, and maybe more years kind

00:42:14.130 --> 00:42:20.220
of an intertial wave that we're
a part of that may be a little

00:42:20.220 --> 00:42:22.872
bit overwhelming, particularly
if we try to move away from it.

00:42:22.872 --> 00:42:25.205
So we're just [? kind of ?]
getting [? carried ?] along.

00:42:25.205 --> 00:42:26.200
AUDIENCE: Very much so.

00:42:26.200 --> 00:42:29.220
DAVID EDWARDS: But
fortunately, that

00:42:29.220 --> 00:42:31.830
is not the whole of human
experience right now.

00:42:31.830 --> 00:42:33.810
And I think that
all I can say, which

00:42:33.810 --> 00:42:37.260
is how I manage my relationship
with Harvard University.

00:42:37.260 --> 00:42:42.120
I'm super delighted and
lucky that Harvard still

00:42:42.120 --> 00:42:44.335
calls me one of their
faculty members.

00:42:44.335 --> 00:42:46.710
But I spend a lot of time
away, and I spent a lot of time

00:42:46.710 --> 00:42:48.190
in my own space.

00:42:48.190 --> 00:42:51.240
And I think that
depending upon who

00:42:51.240 --> 00:42:55.710
you are and the kind of
pioneering you want to do,

00:42:55.710 --> 00:43:00.551
an enlightened organization,
I'm sure Google should give you

00:43:00.551 --> 00:43:01.050
that space.

00:43:01.050 --> 00:43:04.330
Now, it's just important
to understand that Leonardo

00:43:04.330 --> 00:43:07.040
led a really risky life.

00:43:07.040 --> 00:43:08.880
He was not happy
a lot of the time,

00:43:08.880 --> 00:43:11.064
and he didn't feel he
was getting credit.

00:43:11.064 --> 00:43:11.980
He had a lot of stuff.

00:43:11.980 --> 00:43:15.840
And so being out alone,
you have to realize

00:43:15.840 --> 00:43:17.970
that hanging by
your fingernails,

00:43:17.970 --> 00:43:21.510
it looks great when you then
got to the top of Mount Everest,

00:43:21.510 --> 00:43:24.450
but you're mostly
hanging from fingernails,

00:43:24.450 --> 00:43:26.070
and you've got to--

00:43:26.070 --> 00:43:30.800
I personally feel that we
need to all do more of that.

00:43:30.800 --> 00:43:34.940
So that was a rambling response
to your rambling question.

00:43:34.940 --> 00:43:37.740
AUDIENCE: Well I have a very
directed short follow, I guess.

00:43:37.740 --> 00:43:38.948
DAVID EDWARDS: I'm sorry, OK.

00:43:38.948 --> 00:43:40.950
AUDIENCE: What are some
of the interventions--

00:43:40.950 --> 00:43:43.050
I guess specifically, you
mentioned the foundation

00:43:43.050 --> 00:43:44.430
that went to Cambridge.

00:43:44.430 --> 00:43:47.130
And then I'm sure in your
development of insulin,

00:43:47.130 --> 00:43:49.710
that you had opportunities
or things that

00:43:49.710 --> 00:43:51.517
unlocked that ability for you.

00:43:51.517 --> 00:43:52.350
DAVID EDWARDS: Yeah.

00:43:52.350 --> 00:43:53.760
AUDIENCE: And so I
was just wondering,

00:43:53.760 --> 00:43:56.160
without getting too much into
the weeds of policy, what

00:43:56.160 --> 00:43:58.620
are specific things you've seen
besides what you've already

00:43:58.620 --> 00:44:02.640
mentioned that have worked
for people who maybe otherwise

00:44:02.640 --> 00:44:05.166
would not have had
the opportunity?

00:44:05.166 --> 00:44:17.660
DAVID EDWARDS: Well, let
me say that in my case--

00:44:17.660 --> 00:44:20.730
and again, I write
about it in the book,

00:44:20.730 --> 00:44:23.130
and I also point this out
in other creator lives--

00:44:25.890 --> 00:44:33.810
I have found that in pursuing
my dreams to the extent

00:44:33.810 --> 00:44:36.760
that my dreams matter
more than just to me,

00:44:36.760 --> 00:44:39.930
I have very frequently
come to the edge

00:44:39.930 --> 00:44:42.810
where, my god, this could be it.

00:44:42.810 --> 00:44:49.260
And I always found someone
who came and helped.

00:44:49.260 --> 00:44:51.510
And this notion of
activator, which

00:44:51.510 --> 00:44:53.090
obviously in the
Italian Renaissance,

00:44:53.090 --> 00:44:54.506
there are some
really famous ones.

00:44:54.506 --> 00:44:55.950
But they're
everywhere right now.

00:44:55.950 --> 00:44:59.790
And one of the great joys
of my own creative life

00:44:59.790 --> 00:45:02.150
is the discovery
that I'm not alone,

00:45:02.150 --> 00:45:05.620
and that there's this network.

00:45:05.620 --> 00:45:12.115
And so in the inhaled insulin
case, I was a theoretical guy.

00:45:12.115 --> 00:45:13.490
I'd written a
couple of textbooks

00:45:13.490 --> 00:45:16.530
that five people in the
world had read, and published

00:45:16.530 --> 00:45:17.320
this article.

00:45:17.320 --> 00:45:21.150
And I had a series of people, a
venture capitalist I mentioned

00:45:21.150 --> 00:45:23.370
who was more than a venture
capitalist who played

00:45:23.370 --> 00:45:24.630
a really big role in my life.

00:45:24.630 --> 00:45:26.070
But many, many,
many, many people.

00:45:26.070 --> 00:45:28.980
So is there a recipe?

00:45:28.980 --> 00:45:30.060
I don't know.

00:45:30.060 --> 00:45:32.430
I have lived for
many years in Paris,

00:45:32.430 --> 00:45:33.960
and have had lots
of conversations

00:45:33.960 --> 00:45:38.010
with the French government,
and academia in France about,

00:45:38.010 --> 00:45:40.994
how do we create
Harvard in Paris?

00:45:40.994 --> 00:45:41.785
Is it an endowment?

00:45:41.785 --> 00:45:42.900
Is that what we need?

00:45:42.900 --> 00:45:47.460
And so my big point-- and maybe
this is the most concrete thing

00:45:47.460 --> 00:45:49.560
I can say--

00:45:49.560 --> 00:45:53.580
there's an amazing education
in France in many ways,

00:45:53.580 --> 00:45:58.560
and really such bright people,
and such a rich culture.

00:45:58.560 --> 00:46:03.990
But one thing that does not
thrive there, speaking really

00:46:03.990 --> 00:46:09.380
generally, is as a student,
when I leave the university,

00:46:09.380 --> 00:46:12.840
there's not a possibility
to take a big risk

00:46:12.840 --> 00:46:17.190
and do really, really
well really quickly.

00:46:17.190 --> 00:46:21.810
It's more of a climb the
ladder kind of phenomenon.

00:46:21.810 --> 00:46:30.570
And I think that the creating of
opportunities for the dreamers

00:46:30.570 --> 00:46:33.660
is the most important thing
that we can possibly do.

00:46:33.660 --> 00:46:36.960
And I think it is a
challenge for big successful

00:46:36.960 --> 00:46:38.820
organizations to create
those, because it's

00:46:38.820 --> 00:46:42.630
hard to measure the value
of the little experiment

00:46:42.630 --> 00:46:46.390
in the context of
the big, big mission.

00:46:46.390 --> 00:46:48.360
But that's betting.

00:46:48.360 --> 00:46:50.190
And maybe I'll
finish by just saying

00:46:50.190 --> 00:46:54.270
that I was just in Atlanta
speaking to some people,

00:46:54.270 --> 00:46:59.730
and the question was, well,
what can we most do to our kids,

00:46:59.730 --> 00:47:03.480
and to help them create a world
that they want to live in,

00:47:03.480 --> 00:47:05.295
and create what matters?

00:47:05.295 --> 00:47:07.920
And my point to them again, it's
the point I make in the book--

00:47:07.920 --> 00:47:11.040
is that the best thing we
can do, I think, to our kids

00:47:11.040 --> 00:47:13.420
is help them see
that they matter.

00:47:13.420 --> 00:47:16.530
And so I think that
you can't create

00:47:16.530 --> 00:47:20.170
anything that matters if you
don't feel you matter first.

00:47:20.170 --> 00:47:24.780
And so that, mattering for
me has generally been people

00:47:24.780 --> 00:47:27.990
from my dad to lots of people,
my wife, lots of people

00:47:27.990 --> 00:47:30.750
who've bet on me in a certain
way and said, you matter.

00:47:30.750 --> 00:47:34.995
And so that's the easy answer.

00:47:34.995 --> 00:47:37.959
AUDIENCE: What does
it mean to matter?

00:47:37.959 --> 00:47:39.750
DAVID EDWARDS: What
does it mean to matter?

00:47:39.750 --> 00:47:43.740
Well, as I say a little bit,
and I say more in the book,

00:47:43.740 --> 00:47:46.190
almost anything
matters at some moment.

00:47:46.190 --> 00:47:48.390
A raindrop matters that
some moment, right, and so

00:47:48.390 --> 00:47:49.480
everything matters.

00:47:49.480 --> 00:47:50.820
So it's a provocation.

00:47:50.820 --> 00:47:53.430
But what it means in
the title of my book,

00:47:53.430 --> 00:47:56.520
these are things that matter
not just to you, but to many,

00:47:56.520 --> 00:47:58.390
and for a long period of time.

00:47:58.390 --> 00:48:01.200
And so a way to translate that--

00:48:01.200 --> 00:48:03.418
even that, if you dig
into it is kind of--

00:48:03.418 --> 00:48:08.290
but they matter so much that
people want them to endure,

00:48:08.290 --> 00:48:09.890
and so they will
help them endure.

00:48:09.890 --> 00:48:12.590
It's like what you want of your
kid when your kid leaves home.

00:48:12.590 --> 00:48:15.110
You want the kid to thrive.

00:48:15.110 --> 00:48:19.280
And that's not just your girl
being really entrepreneurial,

00:48:19.280 --> 00:48:23.280
but people wanting her, people
wanting her in the room.

00:48:23.280 --> 00:48:26.240
And so creating
something that matters

00:48:26.240 --> 00:48:28.130
is creating something
that's alive

00:48:28.130 --> 00:48:31.220
and that has a right to live.

00:48:31.220 --> 00:48:34.570
[APPLAUSE]

